segments.text: 18th of December.
No, I'll take it back.
20th of December.
20th of December.
Tell me about that.
This was shortly after we deployed to Kunming.
Prior to that, the Japanese
had taken over so-called French Indochina at that time.
They were operating a training base out of Hanoi to train their bomber pilots.

And they had used the route from Hanoi to Kualian and to Kunming to bomb those cities, Kunming being a key city in the southern part of China, and also a big air base, and Kualian being another main supply base of the southern part of China, the south central part.
And they had no opposition whatsoever.
They sent me green crews up there, just bombing the city and the air base, trying to hit the air base.
So when we got up there, that's one of the things we began to wait for.
Well, as I say, we went up on the 14th and on the 20th.
Now, I'd been on, as soon as we got up there, we went off on some scramble missions, expecting them the very next day, 15th, 16th, 17th, and this was full of that for a while.
So you were waiting for the bombers to hit you
from Hanoi, but they didn't.
We know for a fact that several raids took off and shortly after they got over the Chinese border, about halfway up the turnaround went back.
Why is that?
We know they had their own intelligence contacts in Kunming and they knew we were up there and they knew we had scrambled to get in the air.
As a matter of fact, we had a Chinese spy
on the hillside right opposite the air base at Hanoi.
We knew exactly when they took off.

And we also had in China, and that's one thing that General Chennault helped the Chinese develop in the late 30s, was a ground observer core system where the Chinese—we attempted to do that here in the earlier days in NORAD and ADC in the United States, which was useless.
But over there, that's all they had, and the ground observer core worked with their
meet telephone and signal systems, get word about an air raid coming up to Kunming, and that's how we were alerted.
That's what we scrambled on.
Eventually, they got a few radars over there through the land-leash system, but we got word on the morning of the 20th that the raid had taken off, and it was, I think it was 14 bombers.
Ten bombers.
Ten bombers.
Ten Japanese bombers were en route.
So you scrambled.
We had about 20,000 feet just approaching Kunming.
So you scrambled.
We knew they were on their way up, and I think we were at 20,000 feet in an area southeast of Kunming.
I think we had 14 airplanes.
We had to divide what we shot down by 14 people to get credit for our $500.
We know this.
Not one single one of those 10 airplanes ever got back across the Chinese border.
No kidding.
You nailed all of them.
But we didn't account for them.
In other words, the pilot didn't come back and say, I shot this one down, I shot that one.
I came back and claimed two probables.
It was my first combat.
I had gotten so close to one, you know, my ego was like a toilet bowl.
We just couldn't wait.
And once the fighting started... Well, tell me when it started.
Tell me about that.
We climbed up.
We knew they were coming.
And the usual taxes, we'd climb up to altitude about 20,000 feet.
Now, you're getting higher than 20,000 feet in a P-40, and, you know, you just have to operate at max volume.
You don't have any reserves.
And generally, the Japanese never flew above about 18,000 feet.
So that gave us about 2,000 foot altitude, which is all we needed.
Well, coming down on top of them, you know, you'd pick up speed.
And we'd have a band of speed, and I'd hit and run and come back, hit and run, peel off, come back, hit and run.
And we finally saw this formation.
All of them were in one formation of ten of them, a V. And of course, they had the right to come in.
We immediately started attacking them.
Once we started the attack, we were in elements of four, about, I think it was fourteen airplanes.
And three or four in each?
Four in each section, so it had to be two of us separate.
And which ones in the V did you strike out first?
Well, whenever, the minute we saw them, we started after them.
Well, of course, all fourteen airplanes didn't arrive at the same time.
See, in the formation we'd have, we'd have what's called
The attack section would be four.
There would be a support section about maybe 1,000 feet higher than them, a little behind them.
Yeah.
And then the reserve, another four at the top altitude, maybe 1,000 feet above, still further behind them.
Sure.
And, of course, everybody's looking, and we're flying back into loose formation to stand together to keep the airplanes within sight of each other.
Once you saw the formation, you know, you pass a word, and everybody sees the formation.
Sure.
Well, then, of course, everybody pushes forward and gets there and maybe checks their guns even.
And then we start, well of course, the closest flights of one, that's another thing that was peculiar to some.
The first guy that got there was the first guy, I mean the one nearest was always the first one that got there.
And from then on, boy, it was a fight about getting in your position.
I've had to be amongst the pilots to get the attack, to make the first attack on the bomber.
It was that eager.
The first airplane, of course, in the lead, the boys would see him at the same time.
He's the first one to go make the attack.
Well, the rest of them then come by, and then, you know, you're peeling around to come back.
And from then on, boy, it's a fight as to who's going to do it, like a bunch of chickens getting up there, birds, I mean, as to who's going to get in there and make that attack.

And several times, I remember just about ready to, you know, my attack, to start firing, here's a P-40 coming and slip, you know, he turned and turned, and he slipped right in front of me, and I couldn't shoot.
because he was trying to get in there and shoot too.
We were just absolutely swarming all of them.
That's the correct word.
Just swarming.
And whether it was another guy flying on my wing, I was letting him fly forward.
You were in the attack four.
I didn't know yet.
You were in the attack four.
What about the other eight now?
Pretty soon they all came.
They couldn't stay out.
Oh, no, all of them.
I don't know who shot who down, but I do know I came back and had some...
I had some holes in my rear right tail fin, tail stabilizer, and I had to have those patched up.
And I claimed two probables, but we saw about four airplanes go down during the time we was fighting them.
Actually saw four fall out of formation, because they immediately turned and started running.
But we got word from our intelligence that not one single airplane of those got back to base.
But we only claimed, I think we claimed credit for four.
And we divided the four 2,000 bucks among 14 of us, because we're not sure, you know, who knocked who down.

And subsequent fights, particularly between fighters and fighters, you know, where you're maneuvering, you know whether you're going to shoot this guy down or not, because you're the only one behind him.
Now, did you have a camera in the nose of the plane?
No.
We had cameras.
We had one P-40 that eventually we tried to put a camera in to use as a reconnaissance airplane, but...
The basis on which we claimed aircraft was the polished word plus your wingman or another guy seeing it go down.
That's the basis on which we claimed.
Sometimes, I dare say there may have been a little bit of cheating on it, but I don't think there was very much.
I know this, the number that we shot down.
For instance, the British intelligence

When we evacuated Burma and, you know, then finally ran the Japanese down, the British intelligence claimed that there were almost 600 Japanese airplanes, wrecked airplanes, found in the southern part of Burma, and I know we didn't claim over 120 or something like that.
But, now when these bombers saw you, when these ten bombers saw you, did they, did they
try to put up a fight and get to their bombing objective?
Or did they just turn and run?
They mainly made a gradual turn, stayed in perfect formation.
They never broke formation.
I give credit for that.
Boy, they stayed right in formation.
See, that's the only defense.
Of course, we'd pick the guys off from each end.
We'd pick the last man on the Vs. Yeah, because they did have a little return rear-firing gun in a bucket that fell down and went back.
The rear gunner would shoot back.

you get behind, you know, get in the middle of the V, trying to shoot down the middle one down, you've got all this fire, where if you come on the end, my favorite tactics, and many others did the same thing, was to get way out, you know, where you have altitude, and come down, get, come down next to him, was to get, pick up speed, and then come up at a lower, about a lower quarter attack, and shoot, and then break off.
That was my favorite tactic.
And that was my best gunnery.

had my gunnery, had I been, you know, had time to be really trained, had I been a typical fighter train pilot, like the average American fighter pilot, I'm sure I could have had 50 to 60 airplanes of my credit.
But I just wasn't trained in gunnery, aerial gunnery.
See, I was, ever since I graduated, I was in B-17.
Uh, so you people did see four drop, and those were the last four.
Uh,
Well, that's when we broke off the time, see.
Why'd you break off the time?

Well, we were getting, we caught on southeast of, uh, of, uh, of, uh, of, uh, of, uh, of, uh, of, uh, of, uh, of, uh, of, uh, of, uh, of, uh, of, uh, of, uh, of, uh, of, uh, of, uh, of, uh, of, uh, of, uh, of, uh, of, uh, of, uh, of, uh, of, uh, of, uh, of, uh, of, uh, of, uh, of, uh, of, uh, of, uh, of, uh, of, uh, of, uh, of, uh, of, uh, of, uh, of, uh, of, uh, of, uh, of, uh, of, uh, of, uh, of, uh, of, uh, of, uh, of, uh, of
And allow a little bit to get maybe lost, you know, in trying to find yourself again.
Pretty soon you break off the combat and it, and of course, the little commercial radios we had, sometimes you hear the boss, I mean the commander call in and say, okay, it's breaking off, go back.
And sometimes you don't, you just do it on your own.
And a lot of our combat was that way, where they'd just, we'd wait until the last one's dragging in.
Some guys wouldn't get back.
So you guys were getting low on gas?
Oh, yeah.
Did you lose any of your airplanes?
Oh, yeah.
On this particular attack?
I don't think we lost any on that.
Sandy began calling us off and wagging his wings for joining us.
By this time, we were some 200 miles from Columbia.
Oh, I see.
So you were 200 miles.
14 of us had taken off.
Okay.
And we couldn't afford to lose any aircraft after such a fight.
We found a base landing.
The strike was followed in one by one.
We had critiqued the detail.
We could treat the flame, detail included.
We had gotten four of the bombers ashore and several more as probable.
I felt fairly convinced of having contributed to the loss of that left wingman.
We were in high spirits, snarled with the ladies.
It was our first test of combat and our first test.
We had not lost a man.
Not a man, no one, no wounded, or no, uh, right?
No.
When on the ground in the parking area, I found in my maven's eye a bullet hole in my right aileron, right stabilizer and rudder.
I reflected back now about that quiver in my coat.
I remember that.
I remember this very day, all of a sudden, I felt it.
Your airplane was quivering?
Yeah, and the stick.
Oh, I see.
The rudder, the whole airplane.
Boy, you get bullet holes in your airplane.
So it was quivering, and you were coming in for a landing, and you were— No, no, that's when, actually in combat, I got the return fire from one of the bombers.
Oh, I see.
See, that's when a bullet hole went through my—that's when a bullet hole went through.
Oh, this happened in combat, too.
I bet you Chenault was really happy with you.
Oh, yeah.
And that reminds me, let me make one comment before I close.
I know you're going to ask this question.
Sure, go right ahead.
You know what?
Now this is subsequent to, this one I was down in Rangoon later on, but I just want to make this comment to you now.
This was in a fight, I think my first fight with Japanese fighters.
Well, we're going to go through all of these.
We're going to continue on these missions.
Well, this is when I shot down three airplanes in combat.
Well, we're going to get to that.
Unbelievable.
This is our only day.
Unbelievable.
Yet, I subsequently was to see the same lopsided victories over and over.
Expertise from training, confidence, and high morale is a hard combination to beat.
When experience is added, one becomes super.
To me, that's the explanation of the flying tiger.
We were unbeatable and we knew it.
And
It wasn't Glenn's fault.
That first mission must have really blew them around.
Well, of course, right after that, the boys at Rangoon began to get locked in combat practically every day.
They'd come up with figures, you know, at the end of the day with nobody lost and maybe
maybe 15 shot that.
I think one day we shot down 21 airplanes and ran through them, 21 Japanese and didn't lose a man.
That's in four days of four different fights.
Well we're going to get to that now.
The first mission you had was the 20th of December, what was the next one?
For me, well
I don't actually remember getting in a fight with, I've scrambled on some flights up at Cunnameen.
By the way, the bomber didn't come over for about two or three weeks after that.
No.
About two or three, ten days or anything.
I remember scrambling against- Did he ever hit the city?
Never hit the city again.
No.
One time about three- Did he ever drop any bombs on the city?
No.
One time about, must have been April or May.
where we were dispersed at Chongqing and Kuilin and practically no airplanes would come in.
I think they made a run up there and did actually hit the city with two or three bombers one night.
But to answer your question about the next fight, I was on several scrambles out of Kunming where we know bombers were on their way up, but they never got to the city and we never saw them.
I don't think I had actual contact with the enemy until following late January when my squadron, or I was, most of my squadron was picked to go to Rangoon.
Okay.
Late January 1942.
At Rangoon.
Tell me about that.
On the... January the 29th, 1942 was my first fight at Rangoon and this is when
one of those typical fights.
This is a typical fight we had at Rangoon and we, our squadron was there until the 27th or 28th of February at which time we had to evacuate.
We would fight two to four times a day actually meeting the Japanese.
I'd say about four or five times out of each week.
And this was what I'm about to describe to you.
It would be a typical combat, typical fight.
We had a
We were at Mingledon Air Base, RAF base at Rangoon, and we had the benefit of an RAF radar that was installed nearby to warn of the Japanese coming across from the full main Singapore mainland area.
We would
take every airplane off we could get off.
And it'd be anywhere from, say, 8 to 10, maybe 12 sometimes.
Plus, the British could touch, but they'd have maybe two or three boosters or three or four Hurricanes.
They'd get them off.
And we'd all scramble, get off just as fast as we could.
And actually, I've seen flights thread each other at the intersection of the runway in our haste to get off.
Personally, we never had an aircraft taken off.

I remember taking off several times, and instead of going through the normal procedure of checking the mags, you know, right and left mags, I wouldn't do it because I knew darn well I'd have such a drop that I'd just have a little bit of doubts and I wouldn't take off.
Who do you mean your mags?
That's a magneto.
Oh, okay.
You check the engines.
Okay, okay.
And it's normal procedure, and this is a proper plane.
Sure.
And...
I knew I wouldn't take off.
I couldn't justify the takeoff, logically.
Why?
Because of bad engine.
Oh.
And possibility of it conking out on the air, then you lose the airplane.
Sure.
In other words, it did need some maintenance on it, tuning up or something.
But just go ahead and take off.
Whatever runs good enough, you know.
And the minute you get off and get your wheels tucked up and get all the garbage tucked in, you know, and flying clean, you begin to relax a little.
And, of course, then is when you're getting ready to get to fight.
But then you begin to relax.
That was
the most tense minutes is to hear the scrambles fall.
That's the shocking thing.
Then rush to your airplane, hoping that you can get in the airplane, get everything on, get the engines to it, and get off that runway before the bomb maybe hits you or a strafe.
That's the most tense part of any scramble.
But then, the minute you get in the air, see, then you have maneuverability.
Maybe you get out of the way, and you see them coming.
And you haste to have a chance to fight back, because you can point your airplane at them and shoot.
Then you begin to relax a little.
And then, of course, we'd join up, get up.
Then we'd immediately go to 20,000 feet, and then we'd start circling.
And like I say, there'd be, well, there'd be at least a flight of four each.
Now, if there was an extra two, he'd tack on maybe a flight of six.
And the booster boys, maybe they'd be nearby with three or four airplanes, maybe two.
And we'd be generally in the same area where we could at least, you know, catch a glimpse of one another.
We wouldn't fly in tight formation.
And eventually, one of us would see this swirling mass of Japanese fighters coming over on a fighter suite.
And I, it looked straight at me.
Just a straight, basically?
Uh, yeah.
And to catch us in combat in the air with the idea of whipping us, shooting us down.
In other words, it was a battle, air battle, to eventually wipe us out.
They always thought, I don't know why, they just never would learn.
They always thought they could destroy us.
They didn't figure we had many airplanes.
And they were right.
We didn't have many.
But they just never did succeed in knocking us out where we couldn't fight back.
And...
there's no doubt we must have shaken them up morale-wise.
We're bound to because of the odds.
They knew what they lost.
And yet every time they come over, we still have eight or ten airplanes up there.
And you can imagine coming over with 120 airplanes, seeing eight airplanes against you, you know darn well, well, these guys can't have many more.
If we just keep up this few days, we might lose some, but they're bound to lose those.
Well, we never did.
But this is the way we'd meet.
And it'd be just a
looked like a haggle of bees, a swarm of bees.
No formation at all, but they would move.
For them, for the Japanese, no formation at all.
And they'd move toward, you know, always moving towards Rangoon, eventually in Gages.
This is how it was on the 29th of January.
Right.
And somebody saw them, and then, of course, all of us...
They'd give us direction by ground, you know, 10 miles north of Pei-Gu, which was a little town outside of Ran-Gun, or just east of the city, and at 18,000, something like that.
We always knew they were around 18,000, so altitude-wise, we knew just about where to look.
And eventually, all of us see them.
Now, sometimes, one flight may never even see this.
You'd think it's impossible with that many airplanes in the air.
that guys wouldn't be able to see it, but sometimes you just don't do it.
I've been up in the air, and sometimes I wouldn't see them.
And boy, it just killed me when I would.
It just killed me to come back.
These guys had been fighting, and I hadn't seen them.
We'd make a point to hoover over each other about this.
But eventually we saw all these airplanes, and then we'd get in a fight.
And again, it was the usual tactics.
Coming down from above and this swirly massed airplane, these were little fighters, little fixed, these were not zeroes at first when we met.
What were they?
These were called I-96s and I-97s.
They were little fixed wing Japanese fighters that reminded me of the early P-26.
A little monoplane, low wing, fixed landing gear, real sharp looking airplane this day with a radial engine on it.
very maneuverable.
They could practically turn around in a common 50-foot lock.
What about armament?
They had two little 7.5-millimeter gun guns.
That's all?
Very light armament.
And practically, I don't know whether they even had an armor plate in them or not.
How about speed?
Oh, very low compared to the P-40.
They'd probably cruise.
They were an easy prey, then.
Oh, yes.
These were.
These were.
But extremely maneuverable.
And if you ever let them get on your tail, then you've had a problem.
You've just been out
couldn't possibly out-turn them.
But you could out-power them.
Oh, yeah.
So, you know, you do tactics.
We'd come down and pick one of them on the end, on the outside of the squirrel.
And I'd just grab mine, and my tactics were just like all the rest of them.
And I'd come down, pick out one guy because of his position.
I figured he'd be about in the right position for me to be on his tail when I got in firing position.
And I'd just stay right with him, completely ignoring all the rest of them.
And as I'd come in,
There's your came in.
Okay, you're describing a situation.
Yeah, I'm coming in on the attack.
As I get into position to shoot, say maybe four or five hundred yards, then close, with intention to close practically by running over it, then I start firing.
And I had, as I say, a .430 caliber gun and a .250 caliber, hoping all of them would fire.
Sometimes I'd hold my trigger down too long, and I'd fire too long a burst, and heat up my guns too fast.
As a result, I'd have a stoppage on my gun and have to cock them again, you know, get them working again.
For the 50s?
For the 50s.
Not for the 30s.
Well, the 30s, a lot of times they'd get stopped up, and I'd hit my, I'd go out of control, and it wouldn't unstop.
Many times I'd go on back to the base, but none of them were for the 30s working at all.
But not on this particular plane.
No.
You're moving in on this one.
Oh, yeah.
On this one bird on the outside.
And I'd close in on him, and being a normal fighter pilot, he probably knew I was coming in on him, and he'd wait until the last minute to return.
Sometimes he wouldn't.
But in this particular case, now there's many of these I had, so I'll try to be, this is typical.
But just give me this example.
Coming in on this guy, he saw me.
and turned at the last, very last, at the correct second.
And I tried to follow, but as I followed, I'd gotten inside of this mess of airplanes, and no doubt there'd been some on my tail.
So I chose not to follow, and I turned off.
I didn't even get to fire my gun at him.
But then I pulled off the side, gained a little more altitude, didn't turn around and come back in, did the same thing again.
This time, I caught one about the same way, and I closed in on him and started firing.
And I began to see smoke come off his airplane and boil down the side of his cockpit.
And I remember practically, I felt as though I had to lift my left wing to get over his right wing as I passed by him.
No kidding.
And I looked back.
You were that close?
Oh, yeah.
Oh, goodness.
You could have touched him.
Well, it seems that close, yeah.
I'd say easily within 50 feet, no doubt.
Did you see the pilot?
No.
One time I saw a pilot in an airplane.
As a matter of fact, it was in the same flight.
I looked back long enough to see this guy trailing off and smoke going down and I figured I got him.
Then I remember that was the first airplane I shot down.
What was your feeling?
I squealed into the light and caught myself laughing aloud, sitting there in my cockpit at some 18,000 feet.
Enough for him.
Got one.
There you are, Hoffman, old boy.
Just a few days before we lost Hoffman in a fight with the Japs.
He was one of the oldest, as a matter of fact, he was the oldest boy we had from the Navy.
And he was in the other squadron and was one of the first pilots we lost in combat.
I think we only lost eight.
And
That was my reaction.
Related?
It's a hell of a thing to say you're related about killing somebody, but related doesn't describe it.
I was exuberant.
I was just beside myself.
And then, of course, I wanted more.
So then I pulled off again to come back.
So you banged off him.
Yeah, yeah.
And he was going down.
Yeah, to do the same thing.
And of course, all this time,
You could look across the whole area and you could see, you could see smoke, streaming smoke of airplanes going down.
You could actually see, catch out of the ground, burning airplanes.
This is just a mass dogfight like you might see in the old movies.
And the next one, I believe the next one was a head-on attack.
Yeah.
I came in and I was going to do my same little stunt, catching the guy on the end and all.
But just about time as I was approaching to get in my firing run, I caught another Jap that evidently had seen me and knew what I was going to do.
And all of a sudden here he appeared right in front of me and we were hitting directly at each other.
And it was close enough to shoot, so both of us started shooting.
I could see, you know, when you shoot your gun, the smoke curls over the wings, trailing, and you see the smoke.
He was shooting at me, and I was shooting at him.
And I didn't feel anything hitting me, but I knew I was hitting him because I began to see smoke curling coming from the Indian cow along the two sides of the airplane.
And at the very last second, I was going to pull up.
But the very last second, apparently, he was going to pull up and did.
And I don't know how to describe it, but just split second thing, you know.
And I started to pull up and then shoved forward violently.
And when I shoved forward, of course, that's a negative force.
And except for my seat belt, I'd have thrown myself right through the canopy, I'm sure, if it wasn't violent.
But my head hit the canopy.
But everything turned black.
as his airplane passed over me, that's how close he was.
So we couldn't have missed each other more than, we couldn't have missed each other more than 20, 25 feet, even closer.
And then, of course, turn around and look at him, and I saw him going down, and I was close enough where I claimed him.
Just like the other one.
He went down there right after that.
Oh, yeah, oh, yeah.
Matter of fact, I think I followed him down a little.
And I was, I remember I was so tense and tight
that, you know, just hardly breathing.
And then, not exuberant, but, you know, just tense.
And then as I watched him go down, then I began to relax, and I started to get elated and exuberant again.
God damn, two or something like that.
And then, after I was over, I started again, and this time I...
They just keep doing this.
That's their formation.
Why didn't they stay in the middle?
Why didn't they move out?
Why did they stick together just as a beehive?
Seemingly mutually supporting one another.
And of course we just picked off the side of them.
Sure.
Especially with a quicker flying.
Yeah, and then the next one I think was similar to the first one where I got him on a rear attack.
And by this time...
Tell me about that.
Tell me about this.
Well, it's similar to the first.
I think I caught him from the rear.
And, oh, this is when I came past him, and our speed differentiation was so small that I actually passed him and could see him sitting in fire in a cockpit.
But, you know, just a quick pass to look over.
Say about 50 feet apart.
So you came up behind him.
Yes.
Similar to the first one, yeah.
And how far were you when you started shooting?
Oh, again, probably four or five hundred yards.
And then you just close up, you know, practically run over him.
And then he got to move over to get by him.
And he was obviously, I obviously killed him, you know, way back because he didn't make any effort to move at all.
He just stayed right in the same position, smoke coming back, black smoke, and then he started going down real slow.
And as I passed by him,
He was sitting in fire in the cockpit.
He was on fire?
Oh yeah, he was dead.
Otherwise, he was bailed out.
Sure.
I don't ever remember seeing Daphne bail out.
What did you feel like when you saw this man on fire?
Well, I just exuberant again.
You know, you don't get like a...
a madman you just get by then you get coldly calculating daring confident you know you can do it sure you're you've won nothing can hold you back it's feeling of winning in
As a combat pilot, a pilot has a feeling of being victorious.
You're good.
You've done your job.
And you just feel elated.
Not nervous.
The actual firing and attacking and seeing him on fire, it's tense.
But it's just like I'm telling you, it's fitness.
But then when you, the afterthought or before is when you get tense.
and nervous about it, and a little bit scared maybe.
